Browser: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10.6; rv:23.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/23.0
Comments: One of the problems with the Ribbon interface as a compared to a typical hierarchical drop-down menu system is that it is state dependent, but that was not simulated here. In your simulation, after clicking on Zoom for example, the next test begins with the user returned to the starting view (Home). In actual use, the Ribbon is left in View after one clicks Zoom. This is helpful if one is using all the commands in the View menu, but if you are going back to formatting, then to view changes, then to Inserting things you are constantly jumping between ribbons. In a pop-down menu system, you always return to the initial state (just the menu bar). I liked your alternate UI better because I did not have to jump back and forth to ribbon pages.

So when the first time the "Chart" icon appeared, I couldn't find it at all on the default UI and only after a very long time did I realize that the "insert" UI tab actually works. If it was in the instructions (that the UI is actually responsive) I missed it. Maybe a demo, where the target appears and then a second later it's highlighted in the UI, esp for tabbed menu items. Similarly, there are many ways to navigate the UI... keyboard shortcuts, the actual menu bar, etc. It should be made clear that only a subset of these are supported.
